    "label": "Excel · Data Splitting — two ways",
    "subtitle": "One ledger in, ten department reports out — first see how AI drives Excel with code, then let Copilot do it in one sentence",
    "difficulty": 1,
    "time": "25 minutes (Part 1 ≈ 10′ · Part 2 ≈ 10′ · compare ≈ 5′)",
    "dataFile": "Data_Case01_Admin_Expense_Ledger.xlsx",
    "html": "<table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>Financial Reporting / Budget monitoring</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core operation</strong></td><td>Split one large table into many, by one column</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Difficulty</strong></td><td>⭐ (warm-up)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Estimated time</strong></td><td>25 minutes (Part 1 ≈ 10′ · Part 2 ≈ 10′ · compare ≈ 5′)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Raw data</strong></td><td><code>Data_Case01_Admin_Expense_Ledger.xlsx</code> (1 sheet, 720 rows)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>App</strong></td><td><strong>Microsoft Excel</strong> — Part 1 uses the built-in code editor (VBA), Part 2 uses Copilot</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h5>1. Business background</h5>\n<p>Every month, the budget team receives the full administrative expense ledger from the ERP — one sheet, every department mixed together. Each department head then asks the same question: <em>\"Can I get just my department's expenses?\"</em></p>\n<p>Today, someone filters the ledger by department, copies the visible rows, pastes them into a new sheet, renames it, and repeats — ten times. It takes half an hour, and one wrong paste means a department sees someone else's numbers.</p>\n<p><strong>Your goal today is to solve this twice, two different ways</strong> — because the pair teaches you more than either one alone:</p>\n<ul><li><strong>Part 1 — see the machinery.</strong> Ask AI to <em>write code</em> (a VBA macro), paste it into Excel, and run it. You will watch, in plain sight, what \"AI operates Office software\" actually means: AI writes instructions, the machine executes them.</li><li><strong>Part 2 — use the product.</strong> Ask Copilot, in one plain-English sentence, to do the same job. Same brain, same kind of work — but the code, the pasting and the running all happen behind the curtain.</li></ul>\n<p>You never need Part 1's method again after today. But having seen it once, Part 2 will never feel like magic — and that changes how confidently you can use it.</p>\n<h5>2. Data description</h5>\n<p>File <code>Data_Case01_Admin_Expense_Ledger.xlsx</code>, worksheet <strong>\"Expense Ledger H1 2026\"</strong>:</p>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Column</th><th>Meaning</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Entry ID</td><td>Journal entry reference (JE-00001 …)</td></tr><tr><td>Posting Date</td><td>Date posted, Jan–Jun 2026</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Department</strong></td><td>10 departments — this is your split key</td></tr><tr><td>Cost Center</td><td>CC code of the department</td></tr><tr><td>GL Account / Expense Category</td><td>10 expense categories (6100–6800)</td></tr><tr><td>Vendor</td><td>Supplier name</td></tr><tr><td>Description</td><td>Line description</td></tr><tr><td>Amount (USD)</td><td>Expense amount</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The data is clean — no traps in this warm-up case.</p>\n<h5>3. Your tasks</h5>\n<h5>Part 1 — the look under the hood (AI-written VBA)</h5>\n<p><strong>Task A (required).</strong> Ask an AI assistant to <strong>write a VBA macro</strong> that: creates one worksheet per department containing only that department's rows (header kept), and adds a <strong>Summary</strong> sheet with each department's entry count and total Amount (USD), sorted largest first. Describe the file and columns in your own words; tell it whether you are on Windows or Mac.</p>\n<p><strong>Task B (required).</strong> Open Excel's <strong>Developer tab → Visual Basic</strong>, paste the macro into a new module, and <strong>run it</strong> (see Appendix A-3 if the Developer tab is hidden). Watch the sheets appear. You did not write a line of code — but code did all the work, and you can <em>read</em> it.</p>\n<h5>Part 2 — the same job, the packaged way (Copilot)</h5>\n<p><strong>Task C (required).</strong> Open a <strong>fresh copy</strong> of the raw file. In the Copilot pane (mode: <strong>Allow editing</strong>), describe the same outcome in one or two sentences — one sheet per department plus a sorted Summary — and ask Copilot to report the row count of each sheet when done.</p>\n<p><strong>Task D (stretch).</strong> Ask Copilot to add a column to the Summary showing each department's <strong>share of total spend (%)</strong>, highlighting any department above <strong>15%</strong>.</p>\n<h5>4. Self-check (both parts should agree!)</h5>\n<ul><li class=\"check\">You have 10 department sheets plus a Summary — <strong>twice, by two methods</strong>.</li><li class=\"check\">The row counts of the 10 sheets <strong>add up to 720</strong> in both runs.</li><li class=\"check\">Both Summaries total roughly <strong>USD 40.7 million</strong> — the two methods agree to the cent.</li><li class=\"check\">The largest department by spend is <strong>Information Technology</strong>; the largest by count has <strong>127 entries</strong>.</li><li class=\"check\">Look closely at the number formats in each result — is anything <em>displayed</em> wrong even though the value is right?</li></ul>\n<h5>5. Think about it</h5>\n<ol><li>In Part 1 you could read every line of what the machine was told to do. In Part 2 you could not — but the result was identical. What replaces \"reading the code\" as your control in Part 2? (Hint: you asked Copilot to <em>report back</em>.)</li><li>Which method felt faster? Which would you trust more for a sensitive file — and why? Would your answer change at 5,000 rows?</li><li>If the ledger next month has 11 departments, what changes in Part 1's macro — and what changes in your Part 2 sentence?</li></ol>\n<blockquote>When you're done, check against the self-check list. Ask the instructor for the reference answers if anything looks off.</blockquote>"
