    "dataFile": "Data_Case03_Invoice_Register.xlsx",
    "html": "<table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>Accounts Payable / invoice &amp; expense processing</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core operation</strong></td><td>Data cleaning + validation + exception reporting</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Difficulty</strong></td><td>⭐⭐⭐</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Estimated time</strong></td><td>25–30 minutes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Raw data</strong></td><td><code>Data_Case03_Invoice_Register.xlsx</code> (1 sheet, ~64 rows)</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h5>1. Business background</h5>\n<p>Invoices reach AP from many directions — the supplier portal, email scans, department admins typing them in. The register that accumulates is <em>almost</em> right: dates typed six different ways, amounts pasted with currency symbols, vendor names with stray spaces and capitals, the odd row entered twice.</p>\n<p>\"Almost right\" is expensive. A duplicate entry can become a <strong>duplicate payment</strong>; a text-formatted amount silently drops out of every SUM. Before this register can feed the quarterly reporting, someone has to clean it — today that someone spends an afternoon on it.</p>\n<p><strong>Your goal:</strong> hand the whole mess to AI with a clear instruction, and get back (a) a standardized register and (b) an exception list a reviewer can act on.</p>\n<h5>2. Data description</h5>\n<p>File <code>Data_Case03_Invoice_Register.xlsx</code>, worksheet <strong>\"Invoice Register (raw)\"</strong>:</p>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Column</th><th>Should contain</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Invoice No</td><td>INV-xxxxx</td></tr><tr><td>Vendor Name</td><td>Supplier's registered name</td></tr><tr><td>Invoice Date / Received Date</td><td>Real dates</td></tr><tr><td>Currency</td><td>USD</td></tr><tr><td>Amount</td><td>A number (credit notes negative)</td></tr><tr><td>Department</td><td>One of the Bank's standard department names</td></tr><tr><td>PO Reference</td><td>PO-2026-xxxx, may be blank</td></tr><tr><td>Status</td><td>Pending approval / Approved / Paid</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p>The register contains <strong>roughly 20 seeded problems</strong> across at least <strong>8 different kinds</strong> (formats, duplicates, blanks, impossible values, naming variants). We won't tell you where they are — finding them <strong>is</strong> the exercise.</p>\n<h5>3. Your tasks</h5>\n<p><strong>Task A (required).</strong> Produce a <strong>clean register</strong>: every date a real date (YYYY-MM-DD), every amount a real number, vendor names standardized, currency codes unified, department names mapped to the standard list, blank rows and true duplicates removed.</p>\n<p><strong>Task B (required).</strong> Produce an <strong>exception log</strong>: one row per problem found — what it is, which invoice, and what action AP should take. Pay special attention to anything that could cause <strong>paying the same invoice twice</strong>.</p>\n<p><strong>Task C (stretch).</strong> Ask the AI to also compute: total payable amount in the clean register, and the count of invoices by status.</p>\n<h5>4. Self-check</h5>\n<ul><li class=\"check\">Your clean register has <strong>around 60 rows</strong> (started from 64).</li><li class=\"check\">Every date column really is a date; every amount really is a number (test: SUM works over the full column).</li><li class=\"check\">You found at least: blank rows, exact duplicate rows, <strong>one re-submitted invoice with the same invoice number</strong> (duplicate-payment risk), one credit note in parentheses, one date that was an Excel serial number, one \"amount\" that isn't a number at all.</li><li class=\"check\">Clean-register payables total (excluding credit notes) is between <strong>USD 3.5m and 3.9m</strong>.</li></ul>\n<h5>5. Think about it</h5>\n<ol><li>Which of the seeded problems would a human reviewer most likely miss on a Friday afternoon? Which would Excel's own error-checking never flag?</li><li>The AI checked ~64 rows exhaustively. At 6,400 rows the manual afternoon becomes a week — what happens to the AI approach?</li><li>What validation rules would you build into the <strong>intake</strong> (portal/template) so this register never gets dirty in the first place?</li></ol>\n<blockquote>When you're done, check against the self-check list. Ask the instructor for the reference answers if anything looks off.</blockquote>"
