    "html": "<table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>Management Reporting / Office of the Controller</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core operation</strong></td><td>Numbers → narrative: draft, restructure, tighten, fact-check</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Difficulty</strong></td><td>⭐⭐⭐⭐</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Estimated time</strong></td><td>15 minutes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Raw data</strong></td><td><code>Data_Case05_Reporting_Pack_Inputs.xlsx</code> (5 sheets)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>App</strong></td><td><strong>Microsoft Word</strong> (Copilot)</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h5>1. Business background</h5>\n<p>The quarter closed five days ago. Management wants the \"flash\" — key indicators, the budget picture, the trend, top vendors, open issues — <strong>now</strong>, not in three weeks when the full pack is ready.</p>\n<p>The numbers already exist. What takes the afternoon is the <em>writing</em>: turning five tables into six paragraphs a director can read in five minutes, without overstating anything.</p>\n<p>That is a Word problem, not an Excel problem — and it is exactly what Copilot in Word is for.</p>\n<p><strong>One thing you must know:</strong> Copilot in Word works with what is <strong>inside your document</strong>. It cannot reach into an Excel file for you. So the workflow is: <em>put the numbers in the document, then ask for the memo.</em> Thirty seconds of copy-paste buys you the whole draft.</p>\n<h5>2. Data description</h5>\n<p>File <code>Data_Case05_Reporting_Pack_Inputs.xlsx</code> — five small, already-summarized sheets:</p>\n<table><thead><tr><th>Sheet</th><th>Contents</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>KPI Summary</td><td>6 key indicators with prior-period comparatives</td></tr><tr><td>Expense by Department</td><td>H1 actual vs budget and utilization per department</td></tr><tr><td>Monthly Trend</td><td>Admin expenses and invoice volumes by month</td></tr><tr><td>Top Vendors</td><td>10 largest vendors by H1 spend</td></tr><tr><td>Open Items</td><td>5 open follow-up items with owners and due dates</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><em>(In real life these are the outputs of the work you did in Cases 2–4.)</em></p>\n<h5>3. Your tasks</h5>\n<p><strong>Task A (required).</strong> Open a blank Word document. Copy the five tables from the workbook into it. Then have Copilot draft <strong>\"Office of the Controller — Q2 2026 Flash Report\"</strong> using proper <strong>Word heading styles</strong>, with these sections:</p>\n<ul><li>Executive summary — exactly <strong>3 bullets</strong>, each quoting the numbers it relies on;</li><li>Key indicators · Budget position · Monthly trend · Top vendors · Open items.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Task B (required).</strong> Make Copilot <strong>edit its own draft</strong>, at least three ways:</p>\n<ul><li>tighten the executive summary to three single sentences;</li><li>rewrite one section for a <strong>board audience</strong> — neutral, no adjective the numbers don't support;</li><li>turn the open items into a clean table with a Status column.</li></ul>\n<p><strong>Task C (required — the control).</strong> <strong>Fact-check every executive-summary bullet against the tables.</strong> Mark any claim you cannot trace to a specific number. Then ask Copilot to fix exactly that claim.</p>\n<p><strong>Task D (stretch).</strong> Add a \"Matters for the Controller's attention\" section: what would you escalate, and why? Draft it with Copilot, then edit the judgment in yourself.</p>\n<p><strong>Save the finished memo to OneDrive</strong> — Case 6 turns it into the board deck.</p>\n<h5>4. Self-check</h5>\n<ul><li class=\"check\">The memo uses <strong>real Word heading styles</strong> (not bold text pretending to be headings) — check the Navigation pane.</li><li class=\"check\">Nothing dropped: 6 KPIs, 10 departments, 10 vendors, 5 open items.</li><li class=\"check\">Every executive-summary bullet traces to a number you can point at.</li><li class=\"check\">At least one claim in the first draft was <strong>wrong, vague, or unsupported</strong> — did you find it?</li><li class=\"check\">The memo reads like something you would actually send.</li></ul>\n<h5>5. Think about it</h5>\n<ol><li>Which parts of your current quarterly pack are <em>judgment</em> (need a human) and which are <em>assembly</em> (this case)? What share of the time goes to assembly today?</li><li>The executive summary is the part management actually reads — and the part with the highest risk of an AI overstatement. What is your control for that?</li><li>If the memo is generated from the tables, the <strong>tables become the single source of truth</strong>. What does that change about how you version and store the pack?</li></ol>\n<blockquote>When you're done, check against the self-check list. Ask the instructor for the reference memo if anything looks off.</blockquote>"
