    "html": "<table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>Management Reporting / Office of the Controller</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core operation</strong></td><td>Narrative → message: structure into slides, titles that say something</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Difficulty</strong></td><td>⭐⭐⭐</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Estimated time</strong></td><td>15 minutes</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Input</strong></td><td>Your Word memo from Case 5 (or <code>Reference_Q2_Flash_Report_Memo.docx</code>)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>App</strong></td><td><strong>Microsoft PowerPoint</strong> (Copilot)</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h5>1. Business background</h5>\n<p>The memo is written. Now the Controller has ten minutes at the management meeting, and needs slides.</p>\n<p>Today that means an afternoon of copying paragraphs into text boxes, hunting for last quarter's template, and discovering at 11pm that the numbers on slide 4 no longer match the memo.</p>\n<p>But the deck is not a new document — it is <strong>the same content, re-cut for a different attention span</strong>. And that is a job you can hand over almost entirely.</p>\n<p><strong>The one rule that makes it work:</strong> PowerPoint builds slides from your document's <strong>heading structure</strong>. A memo with real Word headings becomes a clean deck. A memo of undifferentiated prose becomes mush. <em>Structure in, structure out.</em></p>\n<h5>2. Your input</h5>\n<p>Your memo from Case 5, <strong>saved in OneDrive</strong>. If yours isn't ready, use the reference memo in this folder — it is the same content, properly structured.</p>\n<h5>3. Your tasks</h5>\n<p><strong>Task A (required).</strong> In PowerPoint, use Copilot to <strong>create a presentation from the memo file</strong>. Watch what it maps: sections → slides, tables → tables, and it will draft speaker notes.</p>\n<p><strong>Task B (required).</strong> Polish it with three instructions:</p>\n<ol><li><strong>Titles that say something</strong> — every slide title should be the <em>takeaway</em>, not the topic. (\"Only IT is over budget, at 109%\" — not \"Budget position\".)</li><li><strong>One message per slide</strong> — split anything that argues two things at once.</li><li><strong>Speaker notes</strong> on every slide: what the Controller should actually say.</li></ol>\n<p><strong>Task C (required).</strong> Add an opening slide: <em>\"The three things you need to know\"</em> — and make sure each of the three is a number, not an adjective.</p>\n<p><strong>Task D (stretch).</strong> Ask Copilot to condense the deck to <strong>five slides</strong> for a shorter slot. Then ask what it dropped, and decide whether you agree. (What an AI chooses to cut is a very fast way to see what it thinks matters.)</p>\n<h5>4. Self-check</h5>\n<ul><li class=\"check\">The deck's <strong>slide titles alone</strong>, read in order, tell the whole story. (This is the real test — try it.)</li><li class=\"check\">The numbers on the slides match the memo. Spot-check three.</li><li class=\"check\">Every slide has speaker notes you could actually use.</li><li class=\"check\">Nothing important was silently dropped between memo and deck.</li></ul>\n<h5>5. Think about it</h5>\n<ol><li>Your Case 5 memo took the numbers from Excel; this deck took the structure from Word. What is the actual \"source of truth\" in that chain — and what happens when a number changes at the start of it?</li><li>Slide titles that carry conclusions force <em>you</em> to decide what the conclusion is. Did drafting them change what you thought the story was?</li><li>What in your current reporting pack is genuinely bespoke thinking, and what is re-cutting the same content for a different audience? What share of your quarter goes to the second one?</li></ol>\n<blockquote>When you're done, check against the self-check list. Ask the instructor for the reference deck if anything looks off.</blockquote>"
