    "html": "<table><thead><tr><th>Item</th><th>Details</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Team</strong></td><td>Financial Reporting / valuation review</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Core operation</strong></td><td>Ratio analysis + rule-based flagging + reviewer memo</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Difficulty</strong></td><td>⭐⭐⭐⭐</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Estimated time</strong></td><td>25 minutes (take-home if the session runs short)</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Raw data</strong></td><td><code>Data_Case07_Investment_FV_Rollforward.xlsx</code> (1 sheet, 12 investments)</td></tr></tbody></table>\n<h5>1. Business background</h5>\n<p>The Bank carries a portfolio of unlisted equity-type investments at fair value (Level 3): preference shares, fund units, direct equity in infrastructure companies. Each quarter, the reporting team reviews the fair-value roll-forward and asks the classic reviewer questions: <em>Which positions moved sharply? Which sit far below cost? Which valuations are getting stale?</em></p>\n<p>Today that review is done by eyeballing a wide spreadsheet. The rules are simple and mechanical — exactly the kind of first-pass screening AI should do, so the reviewer's time goes into the judgment calls.</p>\n<p><strong>Review rules (the Bank's, simplified):</strong></p>\n<ul><li><strong>Rule A</strong> — FV/Cost below <strong>0.70</strong>: assess for further write-down.</li><li><strong>Rule B</strong> — quarter-on-quarter FV change worse than <strong>−20%</strong>: obtain explanation.</li><li><strong>Rule C</strong> — method is \"Recent Transaction Price\" and the transaction is <strong>older than 12 months</strong> (vs 30 Jun 2026): the valuation may be stale.</li></ul>\n<h5>2. Data description</h5>\n<p>File <code>Data_Case07_Investment_FV_Rollforward.xlsx</code>, worksheet <strong>\"FV Rollforward\"</strong> — 12 investments with: sector, region, instrument type, valuation method, last transaction date, cost, fair value for each of the last five quarters (FY25Q2 → FY26Q2), and dividends received in H1 2026.</p>\n<h5>3. Your tasks</h5>\n<p><strong>Task A (required).</strong> For each investment compute: <strong>FV/Cost</strong> (Q2 2026), <strong>QoQ %</strong> (Q1→Q2 2026) and <strong>YoY %</strong> (Q2 2025→Q2 2026). Apply rules A–C and produce a review summary with a flag column, sorted so the worst FV/Cost comes first.</p>\n<p><strong>Task B (required).</strong> Chart the portfolio: FV/Cost by investment with the cost line (1.0) and the 0.70 flag line marked, so a reviewer sees the outliers instantly.</p>\n<p><strong>Task C (required).</strong> Copy the flagged rows into <strong>Word</strong> and have Copilot draft <strong>review-note bullets</strong>: what the flag is, the numbers, what evidence to request from the deal team. You edit the wording — the judgment stays yours.</p>\n<p><strong>Task D (stretch).</strong> Portfolio view: total cost vs total FV, and the net QoQ movement in USD millions — the two numbers a Controller quotes in the quarterly meeting.</p>\n<h5>4. Self-check</h5>\n<ul><li class=\"check\">Exactly <strong>3 investments</strong> are flagged — one per rule (one deep below cost, one sharp Q2 drop, one stale transaction price).</li><li class=\"check\">The distressed investment's FV/Cost is <strong>below 0.50</strong>; it fell off a cliff in FY25Q4 and kept sliding.</li><li class=\"check\">Portfolio FV/cost overall is close to <strong>1.04</strong> — healthy in aggregate, which is exactly why line-level screening matters.</li><li class=\"check\">Your chart makes the flagged names identifiable <strong>without reading the table</strong>.</li></ul>\n<h5>5. Think about it</h5>\n<ol><li>The three rules caught three very different problems. Which of them would aggregate-level reporting (portfolio FV/cost = 1.04) have hidden entirely?</li><li>What other red-flag rules from your real valuation reviews could be added — dividends vs FV movement? method changes quarter over quarter?</li><li>Where is the line between what this screening should automate and what must stay a human judgment call?</li></ol>\n<blockquote>When you're done, check against the self-check list. Ask the instructor for the reference answers if anything looks off.</blockquote>"
